style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: Again, I probably have to distinguish between those on benefits and those not on benefits.  The focus of the work on people on benefits is individual</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">based; it is not based on their characteristics.  When they come in, there is a discussion with their advis</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r, if it is Jobcentre</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Plus, as to the most effective way to get them into work.  There is a jobseeker’s agreement, which will take account of individual characteristics: for example, whether a lone parent </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">needs</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to have a certain work pattern.  However, the general policy of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> in this area is to focus on the individual and not to identify particular groups and treat </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> as homogenous groups.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Haskel:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">On the question of disaggregation, when we get the figures quoted they usually include full</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-f